eleases, from Hell’s Angels (1930) to Get Out (2017), to show how Hollywood’s financial dependence on mono prevented filmmakers from seeing surround sound’s full aesthetic potential. Though studios initially explored stereo’s unique capabilities, Dienstfrey details how filmmakers eventually codified a conservative set of surround-sound techniques that prevail today, despite the arrival of more immersive formats.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 0aMotion picturesxSound effects. 0aSound in motion pictures. 0aSoundxRecording and reproducingxDigital techniques. 0aStereophonic sound systemsxEconomic aspects. 0aSurround-sound systemsxAesthetics. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film & Video / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2024z978311079135840uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520976795?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520976795423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520976795/original  a978-3-11-079135-8  University of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2024b2024  aEBA_EMB  aGBV-deGruyter-alles